In Python, you can implement a function to search for the longest common subsequence of two input strings using a dynamic programming approach. This approach is based on the idea of recursively generating all possible pairs of substrings and keeping track of the longest subsequence encountered so far. Here's an example implementation:

```python
def longest_common_subsequence(s1, s2):
    # Initialize a set to keep track of all pairs
    seen = set()

    # Generate all possible pairs of substrings
    for i in range(len(s1) - 1):
        for j in range(len(s2) - 1):
            if s1[i] == s2[j]:
                seen.add((i, j))
                if len(seen) > len(s1):
                    return max([len(p), len(q) for p, q in seen])

    # If we haven't found a longer subsequence yet, return -1
    return -1

# Driver code
if __name__ == "__main__":
    s1 = "abacaba"
    s2 = "abaabc"
    print(longest_common_subsequence(s1, s2))
    print(longest_common_subsequence(s2, s1))
```

In this implementation, we initialize a set to keep track of all possible pairs of substrings. Then, we generate all possible pairs of substrings by starting at index i in s1 and starting at index j in s2. If the character at those positions is the same, we add the pair to the set seen. We continue this process until we have generated all possible pairs or the length of either string is exhausted. Finally, we use dynamic programming to calculate the length of the longest subsequence encountered so far. If no longer subsequence has been found, we return -1.

This algorithm is a dynamic programming approach that allows you to find the longest common subsequence efficiently by keeping track of all possible pairs of substrings and using backtracking to choose the best one. This approach is particularly useful when dealing with large amounts of data where it may not be feasible to brute force every combination.
